{{refimprove|date=April 2013}}
A '''dry run''' (or a '''practice run'''{{hsp}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.word-detective.com/2009/07/dry-run/ |title=Dry Run « The Word Detective |publisher=Word-detective.com |date= |accessdate=2013-04-05}}</ref>) is a testing process where the effects of a possible failure are intentionally mitigated. For example, an aerospace company may conduct a “dry run” test of a jet’s new pilot ejection seat while the jet is parked on the ground, rather than while it is in flight.

The usage of “dry run” in acceptance procedures (for example in the so-called FAT = [[acceptance testing|factory acceptance testing]]) is meant as following: the factory – which is a subcontractor – must perform a complete test of the system it has to deliver ''before'' the actual acceptance by customer.

